      "comment_id" : 122686280,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "When you get a TIMESTAMP (WITHOUT TIME ZONE) from the database it is effectively a LocalDateTime though. Then if you&#39;re mapping it to a java.sql.Timestamp your JDBC driver converts the local date/time data to a number of milliseconds using the system default TimeZone. <code>.toLocalDateTime()</code> uses the default timezone again to convert the milliseconds to a LocalDateTime. This seems relatively safe to me."
    }, {
      "owner" : {
